<subSubSection lastPageId="34" lastPageNumber="35" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="33.[264,1323,1588,1894]" box="[264,366,1588,1613]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis box="[264,366,1588,1613]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[264,1323,1588,1894]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">This genus is monotypic. It is readily distinguished by the relatively short pereopod 5, and in having pereonites 1–3 fused in both sexes. Virtually nothing is known regarding the biology, and there are not records of associations with gelatinous plankton.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[264,1323,1588,1894]" lastBlockId="34.[264,1323,284,430]" lastPageId="34" lastPageNumber="35" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
It seems to be a rare circum­tropical genus. It has been recorded from the Mediterranean Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Stephensen, K." box="[392,607,1788,1814]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="71 - 149" refId="ref30254" refString="Stephensen, K. (1924) Hyperiidea-Amphipoda (Part 2: Paraphronimidae, Hyperiidae, Dairellidae, Phronimidae, Anchylomeridae). Report on the Danish Oceanographical Expeditions 1908 - 10 to the Mediterranean and Adjacent Seas, 2 (Biology-D 4), 71 - 149." type="journal article" year="1924">Stephensen, 1924</bibRefCitation>
), the tropical Atlantic Ocean, off Florida (
<bibRefCitation author="Yang, W. T." box="[1126,1262,1788,1814]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="11 - 39" refId="ref31427" refString="Yang, W. T. (1960) A study of the subgenus Parahyperia from the Florida Current (genus Hyperia; Amphipoda: Hyperiidea). Bulletin of Marine Science of the Gulf and Caribbean, 10 (1), 11 - 39." type="journal article" year="1960">Yang 1960</bibRefCitation>
), the South Atlantic Ocean, off 
<collectingCountry box="[588,742,1828,1854]" name="South Africa" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">South Africa</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Dick, R. I." box="[761,900,1828,1854]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="25 - 86" refId="ref25655" refString="Dick, R. I. (1970) Hyperiidea (Crustacea: Amphipoda) Keys to South African genera and species, and a distribution list. Annals of the South African Museum, 57 (3), 25 - 86." type="journal article" year="1970">Dick, 1970</bibRefCitation>
), the Gulf of Mexico (
<bibRefCitation author="Stuck, K. C. &amp; Perry, H. M. &amp; Fish, A. G." pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="359 - 370" refId="ref30384" refString="Stuck, K. C., Perry, H. M. &amp; Fish, A. G. (1980) New records of Hyperiidea (Crustacea: Amphipoda) from the North Central Gulf of Mexico. Gulf Research Reports 6 (4): 359 - 370." type="journal article" year="1980">
Stuck 
<emphasis box="[1260,1315,1828,1853]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">et al</emphasis>
. 1980
</bibRefCitation>
), the tropical Pacific Ocean, near 
<collectingCountry box="[735,775,1868,1894]" name="Fiji" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fiji</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hurley, D. E." box="[792,965,1868,1894]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="274 - 288" refId="ref26924" refString="Hurley, D. E. (1960 b) Pelagic Amphipoda of the N. Z. O. I. Pacific cruise, March 1958. New Zealand Journal of Science 3 (2), 274 - 288." type="journal article" year="1960">Hurley, 1960b</bibRefCitation>
) and the Indian Ocean (Bowman &amp; McGuinness, 1982). I have also seen specimens from the tropical south­west Indian Ocean (
<taxonomicName authority="Stn." authorityName="Stn." box="[442,606,324,350]" class="Malacostraca" family="Galatheidae" genus="Galathea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[442,551,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Galathea</emphasis>
Stn.
</taxonomicName>
230), the tropical South Pacific Ocean, near 
<collectingCountry box="[1146,1239,324,350]" name="Panama" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Panama</collectingCountry>
(
<emphasis box="[1257,1322,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Dana</emphasis>
Stn. 3960) and the Tasman Sea, off eastern Tasmania (SAMA).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="34.[264,1323,284,430]" box="[312,974,403,430]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
